WEBVTT

00:02.169 --> 00:04.410
<i>NARRATOR".
We lived in an electric world.</i>

00:04.630 --> 00:06.120
<i>We relied on it for everything.</i>

00:06.340 --> 00:08.206
<i>And then the power went out.</i>

00:08.425 --> 00:11.383
<i>Everything stopped working.
We weren't prepared.</i>

00:11.595 --> 00:14.212
<i>Fear and confusion led to panic.</i>

00:14.431 --> 00:16.763
<i>The lucky ones made it out of the cities.</i>

00:16.975 --> 00:19.592
<i>The government collapsed.
Militias took over...</i>

00:19.811 --> 00:22.849
<i>...controlling the food supply
and stockpiling weapons.</i>

00:23.065 --> 00:25.727
<i>We still don't know
why the power went out.</i>

00:25.943 --> 00:29.527
<i>But we're hopeful that someone
will come and light the way.</i>

00:30.155 --> 00:31.520
<i>Previously on Revolution:</i>

00:32.073 --> 00:36.318
This is Miles Matheson. Commanding
general of the Monroe Militia.

00:36.537 --> 00:39.120
CHARLIE: You were in charge of the militia?
MILES: Yes, Charlie.

00:39.331 --> 00:42.198
I killed fathers and sons and husbands,
that what you wanna know?

00:42.417 --> 00:44.454
MILES:
If we don't find him by morning, he's gone.

00:44.670 --> 00:47.332
NORA: The bomb is on the train.
So is your brother.

00:47.548 --> 00:48.709
CHARLIE:
Sitting here, moping.

00:48.924 --> 00:51.586
It won't help us get Danny back
and it will get us killed.

00:51.802 --> 00:53.918
Philadelphia. You coming?

00:54.137 --> 00:56.424
RACHEL: I'll tell you everything.
MONROE: I know you will.

00:56.640 --> 00:58.506
I'm going to have your son here with me.

00:58.809 --> 01:02.097
RACHEL: If you want to turn the power
back on, it starts with these pendants.

01:02.312 --> 01:05.019
- There are 12 of them.
- Ben gave me this.

01:05.315 --> 01:07.727
He said bring it to a woman named
Grace Beaumont.

01:08.527 --> 01:10.859
She knew something
about the power.

01:13.532 --> 01:15.899
CHARLIE:
No. No. No.

01:16.326 --> 01:18.033
[GRUNTING]

01:18.328 --> 01:20.490
The thing about iron is...

01:20.706 --> 01:22.288
...no matter how tough it is...

01:22.499 --> 01:25.787
...you can beat the hell out of it,
mold it into whatever you please.

01:26.003 --> 01:27.459
That's what we do here.

01:27.921 --> 01:31.380
You see, militia soldiers aren't just born.
We make them.

01:31.633 --> 01:33.340
No, no. No. Please. Please.

01:34.011 --> 01:35.126
It's time for you...

01:35.345 --> 01:38.508
...to become an official
member of the Monroe Militia.

01:38.724 --> 01:40.965
No. No. No.

01:41.977 --> 01:43.559
No. Aah!

01:43.770 --> 01:44.851
[BRAND SIZZLING]

01:51.903 --> 01:53.644
SOLDIER:
Hyah, hyah!

02:25.062 --> 02:26.268
Don't you move.

02:31.568 --> 02:33.525
MILES: I know what you were thinking
back there.

02:33.945 --> 02:35.310
Oh, yeah? What?

02:35.530 --> 02:37.862
That we should have saved that kid.

02:38.075 --> 02:40.487
It would've been too risky.

02:40.744 --> 02:42.610
You can't save everybody.

02:42.829 --> 02:46.538
So you gonna rescue some stranger
or we gonna go get your brother?

02:56.677 --> 02:58.418
Oh, my God.

02:59.596 --> 03:01.303
MILES:
Charlie, hang on.

03:03.600 --> 03:05.136
- He's still breathing.
- Charlie--

03:05.352 --> 03:06.763
This isn't our problem either?

03:06.978 --> 03:08.434
AARON:
Son of a bitch!

03:10.357 --> 03:12.064
What the hell?

03:14.528 --> 03:15.643
Where did you take him?

03:16.113 --> 03:17.979
NORA:
Who? We didn't take anyone.

03:21.034 --> 03:22.991
You're gonna poke your eye out, kid.

03:23.704 --> 03:25.160
Where are your parents?

03:25.372 --> 03:27.613
Where's Peter?
What'd you do with him?

03:27.833 --> 03:31.576
- Calm down. Who's Peter?
- Check their arms.

03:40.554 --> 03:43.888
They don't have burn marks, Michael.
It's not them.

03:44.599 --> 03:46.431
CHARLIE:
Does Peter have blond hair?

03:46.643 --> 03:49.135
Was he wearing a green shirt?

03:51.690 --> 03:52.896
MICHAEL:
You took him.

03:53.316 --> 03:57.355
No, the militia did,
the guys with the burn marks.

03:57.571 --> 03:59.858
We saw him being carried away
on a wagon.

04:01.074 --> 04:03.111
What's militia?

04:03.702 --> 04:05.488
Is Peter your friend?

04:05.787 --> 04:07.619
He's my brother.

04:08.999 --> 04:10.114
I'm sorry.

04:10.667 --> 04:12.999
Where the hell are your parents?

04:14.296 --> 04:15.502
We don't have any.

04:17.214 --> 04:18.296
[WHISTLES]

05:00.425 --> 05:03.838
Yeah, no, this is not totally creepy
at all.

05:04.054 --> 05:05.169
They're just children.

05:05.388 --> 05:06.753
<i>Children of the Corn.</i>

05:07.474 --> 05:10.216
What did they do
with their parents, huh?

05:11.436 --> 05:14.428
I'm telling you kids skeeve me out.

05:14.856 --> 05:17.188
In your village,
weren't you the teacher?

05:17.400 --> 05:21.735
Not a lot of employment opportunities
post blackout.

05:25.325 --> 05:27.737
MICHAEL:
Davis, you're in charge while I'm gone.

05:29.162 --> 05:30.448
Slow down.

05:31.498 --> 05:33.580
- Which way did they take him?
- Just stop.

05:33.792 --> 05:37.660
You tell us what happened
to your parents or we're not talking.

05:40.966 --> 05:43.082
It was a long time ago.

05:44.302 --> 05:45.758
Those men came.

05:45.971 --> 05:49.089
The ones with the burn marks
and wagons.

05:49.766 --> 05:52.007
- Why did they come?
MICHAEL: We don't know.

05:52.561 --> 05:54.677
We think it had something to do
with that flag.

05:55.438 --> 05:57.179
We think they didn't like the colors.

05:58.358 --> 06:02.101
Our parents hid us in the basement.

06:02.487 --> 06:04.694
Said they were coming right back.

06:05.115 --> 06:07.607
Peter was oldest so he was in charge.

06:09.119 --> 06:11.861
But then...

06:12.789 --> 06:14.905
...we heard screams.

06:15.166 --> 06:16.497
Shots.

06:18.211 --> 06:19.497
We were all crying.

06:21.298 --> 06:25.542
We waited and waited.

06:27.220 --> 06:29.177
But our parents never came back.

06:30.473 --> 06:32.259
Then we went outside.

06:34.060 --> 06:38.475
The first thing me and Peter saw
was our mom.

06:39.482 --> 06:41.689
And then the others.

06:42.027 --> 06:44.485
All-- All dead.

06:45.530 --> 06:47.362
Peter kept us alive.

06:47.824 --> 06:49.110
He brought us here.

06:49.326 --> 06:52.239
He still tells stories to the little ones
about their parents...

06:52.454 --> 06:53.740
...so they don't forget.

06:57.959 --> 07:01.372
I don't have time for this. I have to go.

07:01.838 --> 07:03.294
Michael, just wait.

07:03.506 --> 07:05.292
MICHAEL:
We'll need everything we have.

07:05.508 --> 07:07.966
You can't go after the militia.
It's too dangerous.

07:08.178 --> 07:10.385
We can take care of ourselves.

07:11.431 --> 07:12.921
What if we do it?

07:15.352 --> 07:17.810
- What?
- We'll get your brother back.

07:18.021 --> 07:19.557
We're gonna do what now?

07:21.524 --> 07:22.855
Why would you help me?

07:25.070 --> 07:27.402
Because the militia
took my brother too.

07:28.907 --> 07:29.988
Did you get him back?

07:31.618 --> 07:33.279
Not yet.

07:33.787 --> 07:35.403
I'm trying.

07:36.122 --> 07:38.409
Charlie, can I talk to you
for a second?

07:47.217 --> 07:49.504
AARON:
This is a bad idea.

07:50.261 --> 07:52.548
Maybe. But we still have to do it.

07:53.014 --> 07:58.350
Look, I hate to say this,
but that is not Danny on that wagon.

07:59.312 --> 08:01.770
Yeah, I know that, Aaron.

08:01.982 --> 08:04.189
If we don't go, those kids will.

08:04.401 --> 08:07.018
They'll attack the militia.
We know what's gonna happen.

08:07.445 --> 08:10.312
They're children.
At least we stand a chance.

08:10.532 --> 08:12.990
Miles, do you wanna weigh in on this?

08:13.201 --> 08:14.236
She's right.

08:16.246 --> 08:20.615
But you just said
that we can't save everyone.

08:20.834 --> 08:24.122
Yeah, well we're saving this one.

08:43.773 --> 08:45.889
We'll track that wagon,
get your brother back.

08:46.109 --> 08:49.397
But you stay here
and stay out of trouble, okay?

09:21.936 --> 09:23.597
We're sitting in a cage.

09:23.813 --> 09:26.680
And you're acting
like nothing's wrong.

09:27.859 --> 09:29.850
We have food.

09:30.070 --> 09:31.936
We have beds.

09:32.155 --> 09:34.317
It could get worse.

09:35.909 --> 09:37.570
- A lot worse.
- Please.

09:38.620 --> 09:40.657
- We have to leave.
- Shh.

09:41.748 --> 09:43.364
They'll hear you.

09:43.583 --> 09:44.994
[DOOR OPENS]

09:45.627 --> 09:49.495
Ma'am, General Monroe
would like to speak with you, please.

09:58.348 --> 10:01.306
MONROE:
Rachel. Thank you for coming.

10:01.518 --> 10:04.476
How's Danny? Is he settling in?

10:05.021 --> 10:06.603
You wanted to see me?

10:08.108 --> 10:10.440
Well, it's these pendants, Rachel.

10:11.361 --> 10:14.695
Now, you've told us about
these seemingly magical pendants...

10:14.906 --> 10:17.273
...that somehow turn on computers.

10:17.784 --> 10:21.368
And yet we've not been able
to find one of them.

10:22.372 --> 10:24.283
I've told you everything that I know.

10:24.499 --> 10:26.081
No.

10:27.043 --> 10:31.002
No, you've sent us to a string
of abandoned houses.

10:31.214 --> 10:34.798
Most of your colleagues
are not where you said they'd be.

10:37.512 --> 10:39.253
Well, I haven't really kept in touch.

10:39.472 --> 10:41.804
I've been out of the loop
for some reason.

10:43.268 --> 10:45.259
No, no, I said, most.

10:45.478 --> 10:47.264
Not all.

10:47.480 --> 10:50.689
We did manage to find
one of your friends.

10:50.984 --> 10:54.147
A Dr. Bradley Jaffe.

10:54.779 --> 10:56.395
Brad.

10:57.073 --> 10:58.234
He's here?

10:58.449 --> 11:01.282
Yes. For three weeks now.

11:02.662 --> 11:04.244
Three weeks?

11:04.789 --> 11:06.325
TOM:
He's been a tough one to crack.

11:06.958 --> 11:09.120
And we've been cracking hard.

11:10.128 --> 11:11.744
Bass.

11:12.505 --> 11:14.917
Whatever you're doing...

11:15.717 --> 11:16.832
...please stop.

11:18.136 --> 11:20.423
As soon as he gives us his pendant.

11:23.850 --> 11:25.716
I'll talk 110 him.

11:25.935 --> 11:29.553
Just leave him alone.

11:29.772 --> 11:32.730
We were hoping that you'd say
something like that, Mrs. Matheson.

11:32.942 --> 11:38.608
And may I say that your cooperation
is warmly appreciated.

11:45.413 --> 11:46.619
[GRUNTING]

11:48.958 --> 11:50.448
Okay.

11:55.298 --> 11:56.788
[PHONE RINGING]

11:57.967 --> 12:00.834
Okay. Show me what you got.

12:01.804 --> 12:04.171
What we've got, Mr. Flynn,
is a mistake.

12:04.390 --> 12:09.100
My partners and I,
we set out to invent a device...

12:09.312 --> 12:12.304
...that generates clean,
low-cost electricity.

12:12.523 --> 12:14.890
We failed completely.
It doesn't work.

12:15.109 --> 12:18.477
In fact, it does exactly the opposite
of what we intended.

12:18.696 --> 12:21.404
Instead of generating electricity, um...

12:22.659 --> 12:23.865
...it inhibits it.

12:24.202 --> 12:29.493
Well, that's a failure,
but it's a very, very interesting one.

12:29.707 --> 12:31.948
Brad, Grace, if you please.

12:32.168 --> 12:34.330
[KEYBOARD CLACKING]

12:38.633 --> 12:40.874
[ELECTRICITY CRACKLING]

12:58.820 --> 13:00.185
[KEYPAD BEEPING]

13:01.072 --> 13:02.233
[DOOR BLEEPING]

13:06.327 --> 13:09.035
So can this be replicated?

13:09.831 --> 13:12.698
- Yes, sir.
- On how large a scale?

13:12.917 --> 13:14.032
RACHEL:
Ben.

13:16.087 --> 13:17.122
What's going on?

13:17.338 --> 13:21.377
Rachel, this is Assistant
Secretary Flynn from the DOD.

13:22.093 --> 13:23.333
Nice to meet you.

13:23.553 --> 13:25.464
Ma'am, I am impressed.

13:25.680 --> 13:28.798
Now, I can't guarantee anything,
of course...

13:29.058 --> 13:32.050
...but I'm gonna recommend
we offer you a full contract.

13:32.270 --> 13:34.682
- Really?
- This little start-up of yours...

13:34.897 --> 13:38.310
...is about to become a very large
and important company.

13:40.111 --> 13:42.318
Ben, a word.

13:43.990 --> 13:45.822
How can you not tell me about this?

13:46.075 --> 13:48.737
I knew you'd react
exactly the way you're reacting.

13:48.953 --> 13:51.661
- Don't get cute.
- A government contract is not the worst.

13:51.873 --> 13:55.616
- With the Department of Defense?
- Rachel, we are crashing and burning.

13:57.086 --> 13:59.919
Another month, we won't be able
to keep the lights on.

14:00.131 --> 14:02.714
The DOD is a lifeline.

14:02.967 --> 14:04.958
What if they want to use it
as a weapon?

14:05.178 --> 14:06.794
Have you thought about that?

14:10.266 --> 14:13.179
You-- You have.

14:20.109 --> 14:21.725
See these?

14:22.612 --> 14:25.104
More than one wagon we're following.

14:25.365 --> 14:28.073
Dozens of treads here
all going the same direction.

14:28.284 --> 14:31.527
- Meaning?
- Nothing good.

14:33.373 --> 14:36.832
- What is up with Miles?
- What do you mean?

14:37.043 --> 14:40.126
I mean, the guy has raised dickishness
to an art form.

14:40.338 --> 14:44.332
And suddenly he's down to rescue some
strange kid? That doesn't surprise you?

14:44.634 --> 14:47.217
- Not really.
- Why not?

14:47.428 --> 14:48.759
Think about it.

14:48.971 --> 14:52.930
Those kids lost their parents,
what, seven, eight years ago?

14:53.142 --> 14:55.634
When Miles was in charge
of the militia.

14:56.646 --> 14:59.513
Those kids became orphans
under his watch.

15:01.943 --> 15:03.274
[BUSH RUSTLING]

15:16.374 --> 15:19.787
MICHAEL:
Hey, let go of me.

15:22.672 --> 15:25.664
- Look what I found.
- Michael, you have to go back.

15:26.551 --> 15:28.883
Pete is my brother. You can't stop me.

15:30.888 --> 15:34.756
It's irritating when a dumb kid
tells you what to do, isn't it?

15:36.269 --> 15:38.351
Fine. Stay close.

15:39.814 --> 15:41.680
[WHISTLES]

15:50.324 --> 15:52.861
I take it they're not gonna turn around
either.

15:53.077 --> 15:54.192
No.

15:57.248 --> 15:58.409
Awesome.

15:58.624 --> 16:01.707
It's like a pack of hairless Ewoks.

16:12.513 --> 16:14.971
Welcome to your new home.

16:39.415 --> 16:41.406
Hey. I'm Nora.

16:42.877 --> 16:47.587
You thirsty?
You want some water? It's okay.

16:49.800 --> 16:52.292
Hey, what are you d--?
Give me that back.

16:59.852 --> 17:01.388
I don't like you.

17:02.897 --> 17:05.480
Feeling is so mutual, kid.

17:05.691 --> 17:06.931
MILES:
Hey, Aaron.

17:08.611 --> 17:11.478
- What's that?
- Nothing. It's my necklace.

17:12.031 --> 17:13.771
Kid tried to steal it.

17:18.287 --> 17:19.742
You seem nervous.

17:19.955 --> 17:20.991
[SCOFFS]

17:21.207 --> 17:22.742
What makes you say that?

17:24.502 --> 17:26.539
You're sweating.

17:26.753 --> 17:28.369
I just ran.

17:28.965 --> 17:31.548
Miles, you gotta see this.

17:48.818 --> 17:50.274
What is that?

17:51.070 --> 17:52.856
MILES:
It's a conscription facility.

17:54.657 --> 17:56.398
A soldier factory.

17:56.826 --> 17:58.408
Kids go in...

17:58.703 --> 18:00.740
...they're re-educated...

18:02.623 --> 18:04.534
...soldiers come out.

18:06.002 --> 18:10.496
It's one thing snatching a kid
off a wagon, Charlie, but this...

18:11.048 --> 18:14.461
You don't just storm a place like that.
It's impossible.

18:29.817 --> 18:31.023
[GRUNTING]

18:35.823 --> 18:37.439
[GRUNTING]

18:38.868 --> 18:40.654
[GROANING]

18:40.870 --> 18:42.201
Please.

18:42.413 --> 18:44.780
Please. Please help.

18:45.207 --> 18:47.414
[MACHINE BEEPING]

18:51.088 --> 18:52.704
DOCTOR:
Okay, look at this.

18:53.215 --> 18:55.126
You see this line right here
by the heart?

18:56.010 --> 18:57.466
Blood vessel?

18:57.678 --> 18:59.385
There are supposed to be two of them.

18:59.597 --> 19:00.632
One's missing.

19:00.848 --> 19:04.261
Baby's not getting enough circulation
to the lungs and other organs.

19:04.477 --> 19:05.808
What does that mean?

19:06.020 --> 19:07.135
What do we do?

19:07.355 --> 19:12.020
We could induce and operate,
but he'll be too weak.

19:12.443 --> 19:14.354
Chances of survival are low.

19:15.363 --> 19:18.481
Or you could carry the baby to term.

19:18.741 --> 19:20.402
The condition will get worse.

19:20.618 --> 19:23.076
It's unlikely he'd survive the stress
of labor.

19:25.665 --> 19:27.030
I'm sorry.

19:29.293 --> 19:30.749
Ben.

19:33.923 --> 19:35.209
He said "he."

19:37.468 --> 19:39.209
He's a boy.

19:45.184 --> 19:46.845
I can't breathe.

19:47.061 --> 19:48.802
[RACHEL CRYING]

19:51.607 --> 19:53.439
[DOOR OPENING]

19:54.610 --> 19:56.442
[MAN GRUNTING]

20:02.493 --> 20:03.949
[GRUNTS]

20:07.707 --> 20:09.539
[RACHEL COUGHING]

20:12.712 --> 20:14.498
Hello?

20:15.464 --> 20:17.080
Who's there?

20:17.967 --> 20:19.549
Bradley?

20:20.803 --> 20:22.259
Rachel?

20:22.471 --> 20:24.178
Brad?

20:25.266 --> 20:27.052
Is that you?

20:28.102 --> 20:29.809
It's me.

20:33.023 --> 20:35.890
It's so good to see you.

20:36.569 --> 20:38.560
We thought you were dead.

20:46.579 --> 20:48.320
Did you hide the pendant?

20:50.249 --> 20:51.660
Yeah.

20:52.334 --> 20:53.745
We have friends here.

20:54.086 --> 20:57.420
Some of the guards
are with the rebels.

20:58.466 --> 21:02.676
If you tell me where it is,
the rebels can go and get it.

21:03.846 --> 21:05.678
Before Monroe does.

21:08.142 --> 21:11.134
- They'll keep it safe.
- No. No, it's too risky.

21:11.353 --> 21:14.061
It's better than Monroe finding it.

21:15.107 --> 21:17.189
He can't make you talk...

21:17.401 --> 21:20.860
...if you really don't know
where the pendant is.

21:26.410 --> 21:28.651
I gotta say...

21:29.205 --> 21:32.448
...I've been wondering
how Monroe knew about the pendants.

21:40.758 --> 21:42.749
I'm not telling anyone anything.

21:43.469 --> 21:45.380
- Bradley.
- This conversation's over.

21:45.596 --> 21:46.836
Brad.

21:51.811 --> 21:55.725
- Uh-uh. Forget it, that's not happening.
- I look the same age as those recruits.

21:55.940 --> 21:59.808
- I could get in, find Peter, get out.
- Hey, I wanted to help, I did.

22:00.528 --> 22:02.144
Not if it means you going in there.

22:02.363 --> 22:05.321
- If I don't, Michael will.
- I said no.

22:07.284 --> 22:08.740
Charlie.

22:09.662 --> 22:11.619
What happens on that boat?

22:12.331 --> 22:13.366
That's my fault.

22:13.582 --> 22:18.201
What happened to Peter and Michael
and their parents...

22:19.338 --> 22:21.670
...and what's happening to Danny...

22:23.926 --> 22:26.918
...that is all because of yours truly.

22:29.890 --> 22:33.884
How do we even know we're
gonna get Danny back? I'm serious.

22:35.020 --> 22:37.136
With our luck? Come on.

22:37.356 --> 22:39.267
I have my doubts.

22:40.442 --> 22:42.524
But we can help these kids.

22:44.071 --> 22:48.065
Then at least all the crap that we've
been through will have meant--

22:48.409 --> 22:50.491
Will have meant something.

22:57.835 --> 22:59.451
All right.

23:01.672 --> 23:03.788
If you're gonna get Peter back...

23:04.091 --> 23:06.378
...you're gonna need a master key.

23:07.219 --> 23:09.051
And that's gonna hurt.

23:20.649 --> 23:22.811
SOLDIER:
Whoa.

23:25.446 --> 23:26.777
So...

23:30.200 --> 23:33.192
What's a pretty girl like you
doing out here?

23:34.038 --> 23:35.745
All alone.

23:35.956 --> 23:38.994
I'm not alone. My family's hunting.
They'll be right back.

23:39.209 --> 23:41.075
A whole family?

23:41.295 --> 23:43.081
And you got just that one little bag?

23:46.091 --> 23:47.456
I don't think so.

24:00.105 --> 24:02.016
[CHARLIE GRUNTS]

24:06.195 --> 24:07.856
[CHARLIE GRUNTS]

24:26.966 --> 24:29.708
So, what? You work for these people?

24:30.344 --> 24:32.335
For Monroe?

24:33.138 --> 24:34.674
No.

24:35.641 --> 24:37.882
I'm a prisoner here.

24:38.811 --> 24:42.304
Brad, they are going to kill you.

24:43.565 --> 24:45.681
There's worse things than dying.

24:45.901 --> 24:47.562
Like betraying all your friends.

24:51.865 --> 24:55.233
All the years I've been here...

24:55.995 --> 24:59.078
...I never said a damn thing to Monroe.

25:00.249 --> 25:02.365
Until he showed up with my son.

25:03.127 --> 25:04.913
My son.

25:05.671 --> 25:09.960
If I don't cooperate, they will hurt him.

25:10.384 --> 25:12.591
They will torture him.

25:13.512 --> 25:15.219
So yes...

25:15.973 --> 25:18.761
...there are worse things than dying.

25:20.728 --> 25:23.186
I'm sorry, Rachel, I am.

25:23.939 --> 25:27.432
But you hand Monroe the pendants,
that kind of power...

25:27.651 --> 25:30.143
...we're talking thousands,
if not millions of lives...

25:30.362 --> 25:31.898
...against the life of one boy.

25:32.698 --> 25:34.609
It's easy to be self-righteous...

25:34.825 --> 25:37.487
...when it's not your child
who's on the hook, Dr. Jaffe.

25:38.620 --> 25:41.408
You should've listened
to Mrs. Matheson.

25:41.623 --> 25:43.830
But she was wrong about one thing.

25:44.168 --> 25:46.660
We're not gonna kill you.

25:49.131 --> 25:50.496
Daddy?

25:50.716 --> 25:52.002
BRADLEY:
Eve.

25:52.217 --> 25:55.255
- Unh! You bitch!
RACHEL: I didn't know.

25:56.555 --> 25:59.388
Don't worry.
We'll keep your daughter safe for you.

26:00.434 --> 26:01.469
Please, don't do this.

26:01.685 --> 26:05.019
But you were the one who told us about
the good doctor in the first place.

26:05.439 --> 26:07.680
After that, it was easy
to dig up his daughter.

26:07.900 --> 26:09.265
- Take her.
BRADLEY: No!

26:09.485 --> 26:11.977
EVE: No, please, no.
BRADLEY: No!

26:12.446 --> 26:15.814
- I didn't know they were going after Eve.
BRADLEY: How could you do this?

26:16.033 --> 26:17.273
Sorry. I'm sorry.

26:17.493 --> 26:19.530
[BRADLEY SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY]

26:20.662 --> 26:22.323
[SOBBING]

26:26.794 --> 26:30.708
My name is Lieutenant Slotnick.

26:31.548 --> 26:33.414
And I wanna welcome you.

26:33.634 --> 26:36.296
I know that some of you
are feeling very scared right now.

26:36.970 --> 26:40.429
But let me tell you
that this is going to be...

26:40.641 --> 26:43.508
...the best thing
that has ever happened to you.

26:43.727 --> 26:48.847
You get the chance to fight and die
for something that truly matters.

26:49.817 --> 26:52.104
General Monroe has led us away...

26:52.319 --> 26:54.981
...from the filth and the corruption
of the United States.

26:55.405 --> 26:57.442
He's given us strength.

26:57.866 --> 26:59.231
And morality.

26:59.451 --> 27:02.739
And the Monroe Republic
will be the greatest nation...

27:02.955 --> 27:04.787
...that this world has ever seen.

27:08.752 --> 27:10.288
You all right there, son?

27:10.504 --> 27:11.960
Step out.

27:15.092 --> 27:16.582
Come on.

27:19.304 --> 27:21.716
Go on, you can speak freely.

27:22.516 --> 27:25.474
I just-- I just want to go home.

27:28.605 --> 27:30.391
All right.

27:30.607 --> 27:32.268
Go on.

27:35.112 --> 27:37.194
You're free to leave.

27:37.406 --> 27:39.067
Anyone can.

27:39.700 --> 27:40.906
Go on.

27:41.410 --> 27:43.196
Really.

27:59.052 --> 28:03.671
[STICK THUMPING AND BOY GRUNTING]

28:12.107 --> 28:14.439
Anyone else feeling homesick?

28:15.110 --> 28:17.317
SOLDIER:
Your quarters are this way.

28:19.990 --> 28:22.527
8288, over here.

28:37.674 --> 28:39.881
- Watch where you're going.
- What's your problem?

28:40.093 --> 28:41.549
Maybe you, ever thought of that?

28:42.095 --> 28:44.837
- Crazy bitch.
- What did you call me?

28:45.474 --> 28:47.590
Look, I'm not gonna hit a--

28:49.311 --> 28:51.018
AW. That hurt? Unh!

29:20.384 --> 29:23.593
Look, Charlie's tough.
She'll get your brother back.

29:23.804 --> 29:25.010
Trust me.

29:25.264 --> 29:27.972
Why should we? You're a grown-up.

29:29.601 --> 29:30.887
I'm one of the good ones.

29:31.728 --> 29:33.719
I haven't met any of the good ones.

29:34.898 --> 29:36.639
Now you have.

29:36.858 --> 29:37.939
You wait and see.

29:44.032 --> 29:45.614
[GROANING]

29:45.909 --> 29:47.240
Follow my finger.

29:51.206 --> 29:52.367
Good.

29:54.251 --> 29:56.413
This will help you relax.

30:11.143 --> 30:12.554
[GRUNTING]

30:23.238 --> 30:25.730
You know, I had a feeling
you were trouble.

30:36.460 --> 30:38.326
MILES: She's two hours late.
Something's wrong.

30:38.545 --> 30:40.582
Let's go get them off that boat.

30:47.429 --> 30:48.510
CHARLIE:
No, no. No, please.

30:48.722 --> 30:52.260
You see, militia soldiers aren't just born,
we make them.

30:52.476 --> 30:57.562
And it's time for you to become
an official member of the Monroe Militia.

30:57.773 --> 30:59.355
No. No.

30:59.566 --> 31:00.601
No, please.

31:00.817 --> 31:03.400
No. No! Aah!

31:03.612 --> 31:04.693
[BRAND SIZZLING]

31:16.208 --> 31:17.494
[BODY THUMPS]

31:36.812 --> 31:38.553
Where's Michael?

31:39.064 --> 31:40.429
He went to go get Peter.

31:41.400 --> 31:43.562
You're joking.

31:55.163 --> 31:58.030
[BELL RINGING]

31:58.333 --> 31:59.573
Unh!

32:02.254 --> 32:04.541
[MILITIA MEN SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY]

32:10.720 --> 32:11.755
<i>H9'! -</i>

32:22.607 --> 32:23.938
MILES:
Let's go.

32:25.402 --> 32:27.359
Charlie!

32:27.571 --> 32:29.403
Charlie!

32:29.614 --> 32:31.104
- Charlie!
- In here!

32:31.366 --> 32:33.323
Miles!

32:40.333 --> 32:43.121
I'm okay. Let's get Peter.

32:47.466 --> 32:50.379
Michael sent me. We're getting you out.

32:50.635 --> 32:51.670
[DOOR THUMPS]

32:54.556 --> 32:56.388
[SOLDIER SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

33:09.321 --> 33:12.484
SOLDIER 1: Sure you heard something here?
SOLDIER 2: Sure.

33:18.914 --> 33:21.121
Hello?

33:35.514 --> 33:37.130
[WHISPERING]
Come on.

33:51.154 --> 33:52.770
SLOTNICKI
Hold it.

33:53.323 --> 33:54.984
This kid mean anything to you?

33:55.492 --> 33:56.573
Michael.

33:57.994 --> 33:59.735
- Let him go.
SLOTNICK: Stay put.

34:00.372 --> 34:02.238
Or I cut his throat wide open.

34:09.714 --> 34:11.751
Weapons on the deck now.

34:24.271 --> 34:26.353
[FOOTSTEPS]

34:30.735 --> 34:32.646
[SOLDIER SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

34:35.907 --> 34:37.818
[WHISPERING]
No, no, no.

34:38.034 --> 34:39.695
Not now.

34:42.998 --> 34:45.409
- It's like a firefly.
- Shh.

34:45.958 --> 34:49.121
[ENGINE SPUTTERING]

34:57.012 --> 34:58.878
[ENGINE WHIRRING]

35:00.473 --> 35:02.259
What is that?

36:09.000 --> 36:11.207
SOLDIER 1:
What the hell was that?

36:58.883 --> 37:02.342
I've sent riders to Dr. Jaffe's house.

37:02.554 --> 37:06.548
As soon as we have the pendant,
he and his daughter can go home.

37:12.856 --> 37:14.472
You know...

37:15.191 --> 37:17.307
...you never did tell me.

37:18.111 --> 37:19.727
Tell you what?

37:21.406 --> 37:24.114
How the lights went off
in the first place.

37:26.119 --> 37:30.488
What was this invention of yours?

37:31.207 --> 37:33.665
What could possibly do that?

37:35.503 --> 37:37.540
What difference does it make...

37:37.756 --> 37:41.340
...as long as I can
turn the lights back on again?

37:45.221 --> 37:46.803
[CHUCKLES]

37:58.443 --> 38:00.525
FLYNN:
Rachel, right?

38:01.362 --> 38:02.944
Yes, Mr...?

38:03.406 --> 38:05.147
Flynn. From the DOD?

38:05.408 --> 38:07.024
Yeah, I remember.

38:07.619 --> 38:10.156
I'm sorry if I'm overstepping...

38:10.371 --> 38:12.328
...but I heard about the pregnancy.

38:12.624 --> 38:14.911
Your baby's condition.

38:15.251 --> 38:16.867
You are overstepping.

38:17.086 --> 38:19.828
Of course, and I'm sure
you've looked into all the research.

38:20.048 --> 38:21.459
Yes. I have.

38:21.674 --> 38:24.336
Even the new fetoscopic trial
at Columbia?

38:25.428 --> 38:26.543
It's full.

38:27.472 --> 38:30.635
What if I told you it wasn't?

38:31.643 --> 38:34.351
They're seeing some pretty
incredible results.

38:34.562 --> 38:36.803
Solving the very problem you've got.

38:37.482 --> 38:39.849
I have a lot of friends in a lot of places.

38:40.735 --> 38:43.727
I'd be happy to make a call, get you in.

38:43.947 --> 38:46.735
Give your baby a fighting chance.

38:48.618 --> 38:52.452
And what do you expect
in return, Mr. Flynn?

38:52.664 --> 38:57.079
Look, I'm not such a bad guy.
I just want to help you out, that's all.

38:57.710 --> 39:01.169
At work and at home.

39:02.090 --> 39:04.673
I just want us to be friends.

39:09.430 --> 39:11.717
[ALL CHATTERING]

39:18.022 --> 39:19.763
KIDS:
Peter!

39:19.983 --> 39:21.439
<i>H9'! -</i>

39:22.235 --> 39:23.600
- How are you?
- I'm good.

39:23.820 --> 39:26.312
Good, I missed you guys.
You been doing okay?

39:27.490 --> 39:31.484
You guys.
Oh, my God, I missed you so much.

39:34.455 --> 39:37.117
[PETER AND KIDS SPEAKING
INDISTINCTLY]

39:41.713 --> 39:44.501
What in the hell happened?

39:46.634 --> 39:48.420
- What do you mean?
- I don't know, Aaron.

39:48.636 --> 39:52.675
Maybe I'm talking about when you were
in the lighthouse and it went on.

39:53.141 --> 39:54.848
How did that happen?

39:56.185 --> 39:59.519
- What are you not telling me?
- Fine. Okay.

40:00.148 --> 40:01.309
It was this.

40:03.943 --> 40:07.607
It can sometimes
turn the power back on...

40:07.822 --> 40:10.735
...and bring machines to life
forjust, like, a few seconds.

40:10.950 --> 40:12.987
And I don't know how
and I don't know why.

40:16.748 --> 40:18.159
Where did that come from?

40:18.750 --> 40:19.990
Ben.

40:22.003 --> 40:23.869
My brother gave that to you?

40:24.088 --> 40:28.002
And you have had something
like that...

40:28.217 --> 40:31.801
...on you the whole time
and you haven't said anything?

40:33.097 --> 40:35.008
Give it to me.

40:35.600 --> 40:38.183
- Why? Why?
- So I can smash it.

40:38.937 --> 40:43.647
This could literally be
the most important thing in the world.

40:43.858 --> 40:46.725
Which is exactly why we can't let
Monroe get his hands on it.

40:46.945 --> 40:48.527
- Give it to me.
- I'm not giving it.

40:49.155 --> 40:50.190
Aaron, I swear to God.

40:50.406 --> 40:53.068
I'm gonna beat you unconscious
and take it. Give it to me.

40:53.618 --> 40:55.609
- Go ahead and try.
- Hey.

40:55.828 --> 40:57.364
What the hell is going on?

40:58.414 --> 41:00.576
And what happened in that lighthouse?

41:03.461 --> 41:05.202
Someone start talking.

41:09.467 --> 41:11.208
I think...

41:11.469 --> 41:16.134
...that they came for your dad
because of this.

41:18.559 --> 41:19.970
Why?

41:24.148 --> 41:26.515
There's a woman
named Grace Beaumont.

41:26.734 --> 41:29.066
And just before the militia came...

41:29.570 --> 41:33.814
...your dad gave me this, and told me
to keep it safe and bring it to her.

41:41.749 --> 41:43.581
FLYNN:
Hello, Grace.

41:45.837 --> 41:47.748
Randall, this is crazy.

41:48.172 --> 41:49.958
Just let me go.

41:50.758 --> 41:53.045
FLYNN:
You know I can't do that.

41:53.636 --> 41:55.252
It's too dangerous.

41:55.763 --> 41:58.175
And we both know why.

42:02.770 --> 42:04.306
What do you want, Randall?

42:04.522 --> 42:06.308
Grace.

42:07.275 --> 42:09.892
I just want us to be friends.

42:48.232 --> 42:50.314
[English - US - SDH]
